</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D651CFF97FFF5F10EFA379144FA62" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F10EFA379144FA62" blockId="15.[111,647,1435,1511]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">DIAGNOSIS. — Differs from congeners in some troglomorphic traits, combined with a relatively broad caudofemoral process of the telopod.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D651CFF97FFF5F10EF9A79405FC09" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F10EF9A7910BF9A6" blockId="15.[113,649,1547,1700]" box="[113,258,1547,1573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F10EF98791C4F9C0" blockId="15.[113,649,1547,1700]" box="[113,461,1579,1605]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">
Length 
<quantity id="4CFF9B72FF97FFF5F1BAF9879117F9C0" box="[197,286,1579,1605]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CFF9B72FF97FFF5F010F98791C0F9C0" box="[367,457,1579,1605]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" unit="mm" value="4.1">4.1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F1F7F9E69387FEB7" blockId="15.[113,649,1547,1700]" lastBlockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Coloration entirely pallid, unpigmented. Antennomere 6 about 2.0 times longer than wide, antennomere 7 very short; 6 poorly visible, unpigmented but convex ocelli on each side of head; Tömösváry’s organ transverse-oval, about twice as wide as long.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FE9B9427FED4" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" box="[699,1070,311,337]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Collum with two transverse striae.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FEFB936CFE75" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Thoracic shield with a rather narrow hyposchism slightly surpassing the caudal tergal contour; 9 transverse striae, of which 6 start above the schism and 5 (neither the first nor the last one though) cross the dorsum.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FE5A934FFDAA" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Male pygidium virtually not sinuate medially at caudal margin.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FD99942BFDEA" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">
Male leg 17 (
<figureCitation id="133C2A12FF97FFF5F23CFD99939BFDCA" box="[835,914,565,591]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[113,124,1195,1212]" captionTargetBox="[125,1192,218,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-13@16.[111,1210,214,1154]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Hyleoglomeris speophila n. sp., ♂ holotype: A, leg 17; B, leg 18; C, telopod, front view; D, distal part of telopod, caudal view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4525439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4525439/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
) with a high, rounded outer coxal lobe; telopodite 4-segmented.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FDD893FFFD2B" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">
Male leg 18 (
<figureCitation id="133C2A12FF97FFF5F239FDD8939FFD0B" box="[838,918,628,654]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[113,124,1195,1212]" captionTargetBox="[125,1192,218,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-13@16.[111,1210,214,1154]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Hyleoglomeris speophila n. sp., ♂ holotype: A, leg 17; B, leg 18; C, telopod, front view; D, distal part of telopod, caudal view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4525439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4525439/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
) with a rounded syncoxital notch; telopodite 4-segmented.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3C4FD189405FC09" blockId="15.[674,1212,216,908]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">
Telopods (
<figureCitation id="133C2A12FF97FFF5F25AFD18939DFD4B" box="[805,916,692,718]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="16.[113,124,1195,1212]" captionTargetBox="[125,1192,218,1150]" captionTargetId="figure-13@16.[111,1210,214,1154]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Hyleoglomeris speophila n. sp., ♂ holotype: A, leg 17; B, leg 18; C, telopod, front view; D, distal part of telopod, caudal view. Scale bar: 0.4 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4525439" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4525439/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Fig.9C, D</figureCitation>
) with a rather small, roundly subtrapeziform syncoxital lobe flanked by two setose horns crowned with an apical setoid. Prefemur and femur micropapillate nearly throughout. Caudomedial outgrowth of femur wide at base, that of tibia with a pilose tubercle at base.Tarsus narrowly rounded apically, almost pointed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31D651CFF97FFF5F3DAFC1D9435FA02" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3DAFC1D9300FC4C" blockId="15.[674,1210,945,1415]" box="[677,777,945,971]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB83697FF97FFF5F3DAFC7D9435FA02" blockId="15.[674,1210,945,1415]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">
Based on morphological evidence, this new species resembles several epigean congeners from 
<collectingCountry id="F3107607FF97FFF5F526FC5C9495FB8F" box="[1113,1180,1008,1034]" name="China" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">China</collectingCountry>
or Indochina, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D14FF97FFF5F20CFBBC93FFFBAF" authority="Golovatch &amp; Geoffroy &amp; Mauriès, 2006" authorityName="Golovatch &amp; Geoffroy &amp; Mauriès" authorityYear="2006" box="[883,1014,1040,1066]" class="Diplopoda" family="Glomeridae" genus="Hyleoglomeris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Glomerida" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B973EA85FF97FFF5F20CFBBC93FFFBAF" box="[883,1014,1040,1066]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">H. maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24057FEFF97FFF5F282FBBC943EFBAF" box="[1021,1079,1040,1066]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see above), 
<taxonomicName id="4C074D14FF97FFF5F3DAFB9C9309FBCF" authorityName="Silvestri" authorityYear="1917" box="[677,768,1072,1098]" class="Diplopoda" family="Glomeridae" genus="Apiomeris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Glomerida" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="electa">
<emphasis id="B973EA85FF97FFF5F3DAFB9C9309FBCF" box="[677,768,1072,1098]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">H. electa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the sense of 
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B66FF97FFF5F2DEFB9C9434FBCF" author="ATTEMS C." box="[929,1085,1072,1098]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" pagination="187 - 353" refId="ref16459" refString="ATTEMS C. 1938. - Die von Dr C. Dawydoff in Franzosisch Indochina gesammelten Myriopoden. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle n. s., 6 (2): 187 - 353." type="journal article" year="1938">Attems (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and others, but none of these shows the troglomorphic features of complete depigmentation and elongate Tömösváry’s organs. However, the ocelli are still discernible and neither the antennae nor the legs are particularly long. To prove that we face a troglobite, additional observations and material are necessary. In general, 
<collectingCountry id="F3107607FF97FFF5F3DCFAA2930AFAAD" box="[675,771,1294,1320]" name="Vietnam" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
supports numerous karst caves rich in troglobites (
<bibRefCitation id="EF964B66FF97FFF5F256FA81942BFAC2" author="DEHARVENG L. &amp; LE CONG K. &amp; BEDOS A." box="[809,1058,1325,1351]" pageId="15" pageNumber="902" pagination="2027 - 2037" refId="ref16766" refString="DEHARVENG L., LE CONG K. &amp; BEDOS A. 2001. - Vietnam, in JUBERTHIE C. &amp; DECU V. (eds), Encyclopaedia Biospeologica 3. Societe internationale de Biospeologie, Moulis: 2027 - 2037." type="book chapter" year="2001">
Deharveng 
<emphasis id="B973EA85FF97FFF5F2D6FA8193D7FAC2" box="[937,990,1325,1351]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="902">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
), while Thien Luong Cave is known to mainly harbour troglobitic arthropods (Deharveng pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
